          <avActivityHighlights>The old snowpack remains quite well bonded.</avActivityHighlights>
          <avActivityComment>In particular high altitudes and the high Alpine regions: Weak layers in the old snowpack can still be released in some place by winter sport participants. This applies in particular on steep shady slopes at intermediate and high altitudes. &lt;br/&gt; Dry avalanches can in isolated cases be released by a single winter sport participant. In the regions exposed to snowfall this applies especially on very steep slopes. &lt;br/&gt; &lt;br/&gt; Even in moderately steep terrain there is a danger of falling on the hard snow surface.</avActivityComment>
          <snowpackStructureComment>Monday: In some localities 5 to 15 cm of snow, and up to 20 cm in some localities, has fallen above approximately 1700 m. &lt;br/&gt; &lt;br/&gt; The weather conditions fostered a gradual strengthening of the snowpack. The old snowpack is largely stable and its surface has a melt-freeze crust that is strong in many cases. &lt;br/&gt; Especially steep shady slopes high altitudes and the high Alpine regions: Weak layers exist in the snowpack. &lt;br/&gt; &lt;br/&gt; In the vicinity of peaks snow depths vary greatly, depending on the infuence of the wind. &lt;br/&gt; In places that are protected from the wind in all altitude zones a lot of snow is lying for the time of year. &lt;br/&gt; &lt;br/&gt;</snowpackStructureComment>
        </BulletinMeasurements>
      </bulletinResultsOf>
